{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958041801/0238.xml":{"full_text":"II!\na\nUnited Labor Jit\nCommittee News 4\nIke Bars Emergency Tax Cut,\nCool to Public Works Projects\nCongress came back from its Easter recess facing a\nPresident and Administration that have turned more strong\nly than ever against anti recession tax cuts and remain un\nsympathetic to large-scale public works\nInterpreting the latest employment-joblessness figures\nwith high optimism, Pres.\nEisenhower told his news\nconference that he saw \u201cno\nneed for emergency action now\u201d\non tax reduction. He indicated\nthat a \u201cdecision\u201d would be made\n\"when the conditions require\u201d it.\n\u25a0nd that studies to determine\nwhen and what is required \u201cof\ncourse could run right along un\ntil the end of the (congressional)\nsession\nHe couldn\u2019t estimate, he\ntold reporters, how long it\nwould be before new highway\n\u25a0nd housing spending would\nproduce actual jobs for the 5.2\nmillion people unemployed as\nof Mar. 15.\nHe thought, however, that\npushing hard on \u201cthose things\nthat are already in progress\"\nwould be better in \u201caccelerating\nemployment than to start new\nand untried projects.\"\nAsked About Meany's View\nAsked about AFL-CIO Pres.\nGeorge Meany's viewpoint that\nthe Mar 15 unemployment fig\nure* meant \"a deepening of the\nrecession rather than a slowing\nof th*, decline,\u201d Eisenhower said\nentitled to his\nMeany\nwas\nopinion.\u201d\nHe himself had \u201conly one re\ncourse,\u201d the President remarked,\nand that was to get \u201cthe very\nfinest opinions from bankers,\nbusinessmen and everybody I\ncan think of, and I have had the\nlabor group in to give me their\nviews, and I think it is just a\nquestion where we have to do\nwhat we believe best\nHis recommendation to the\npeople for combatting the re\ncession was to \u201cbuy\u201d almost\n\u201canything,\u201d but he observed\nthat maybe the people were\ngetting \u201ca little bit disen\nchanted by a few items that\nhave been chucked down their\nthroats.\u201d\nTreasury Sec. Robert B An-i\nderson clearly indicated in a\nNew York speech that the Ad-|\nministration was more worried I\n\u25a0bout possible future inflation\nthan about recession now The I\ngovernment, he said, must \u201ctry\nto avoid those things which\nwould create doubts.\u2019\nI\nNPA Sounds Warning\nThe National Planning Associ-:\nation issued statements based on\na profoundly different attitude\n\u2014the belief that recession is\n\u201ccosting\u201d the nation $25 billion\na year now and that a failure\nto end the decline would reduce\nproduction $40 billion below the.\npotential by the end of 1958\nThe Planning Association,\ncomposed of spokesmen of\nbusiness, agriculture and la\nbor, urged\n\"long range'\npro\ngrams for putting the Jobless\nback to work and immediate\ntax cuts to expand purchasing\npower and \"improve the tax\n99\nTax reduction, the\nsystem.'\nNPA said, should eliminate\nbusiness-burdening excise lev\nies and slash individual in\ncome taxes \u201cespecially in the\nlower brackets.\u201d\nAhead of Congress, as it re\nturned, was a presumed effort\nto overturn Eisenhower's veto\nof the farm bill that would have\nfrozen price supports at exist\ning levels for one year.\nFarm Prospects Dim\nAn attempt to override the\nveto had to be originated in the\nSenate and leaders did not anti\ncipate they could obtain the nec\nessary two-thirds margin\nSenate Democratic leaders in\ntended to take up promptly the\nFulbright community facilities\nbill that would authorize $1 bil\nlion in federal loans for state\nand city public works This mea\nsure, already approved by the\nSenate Banking Committee, was\ndelayed when Republican Floor\nLeader\nWilliam F\nKnowland\n(Calif.) successfully led a drive\nto postpone consideration until\nafter the recess\nAlso set for early floor ac\ntion in the Senate was a com\npromise Douglas-Payne area\nredevelopment bill to author\nize major federal aid to com\nmunities suffering severe and\nchronic unemployment.\nThe senate passed a similar\nbill in 1956 but Administration\nMFL-Cio\"NsW%\nSteel Execs Paid $468,000\nYear9 Senate Group Finds\nSteel executives get paid too much, the Senate Anti\ntrust Subcommittee has charged here in a report on pricing\nin the nation\u2019s number one basic industry.\nThe high payment of directors and top steel manage\nment, the subcommittee declared, encourage labor unions\nto fight for higher and\nhigher wages. More signifi\ncantly, various stock option\ngimmicks developed by the com-i\npanies to pay off their top peo\npie act as a built-in factor driv\ning steel prices higher.\nThese findings appear in a\n203 page report on price prac\ntices in the steel industry. The\n(report is sharply critical of the\nindustry and punctures the in\n\u2018dustry\u2019s argument that recent\nwage increases forced it to raise\nprices an estimated $19.50 a ton\nI during a 12-month period\nI The subcommittee found that\nthe average officer-director of\n(one of the major steel compan\nies collects $468,000 a year.\nThis, it said, \u201cacts as a challenge.\nia red flag, to labor unions and\nindividual laborers to seek all\nthey can get\nto persuade labor to hold a wage\nIt is difficult\nline when it knows the generous\nmanner in which officer-direc\n\u25a0tors compensate themselves.\u201d\nI The subcommittee questioned\nthe accuracy of the belief that\nexecutive compensation is deter\nmined by stockholders. \u201cIt is\ndifficult to believe that stock\nholders exercise this prerogative\nin actuality,\" it observed.\nIn reality, the subcommittee\nopposition prevented its consi\nderation on the House floor.\nThe basic bill to expand\ncoverage of the wage-hour law\nwas still tied up in Senate La\nbor Committee, where the op\nposition of one Democrat, Sen.\nStrom Thurmond (S. C.), and\nfailure of any of six Republicans\nto indicate support of the com\npromise measure sponsored by\nSen John F. Kennedy (D\nMass.) has stalemated action.\nKennedy\u2019s bill would give fed\neral minimum-wage protection\nto about 6 million workers now\nnot covered The AFL-CIO en\ndorsed a bill by Sen. Wayne\nMorse (D-Ore.) to cover 9.6\nmillion workers, but Labor Sec.\nJames P Mitchell refused to\nendorse any measure going be\nyond the Administration pro\nposal to add 2.5 million workers\nand to deny even these workers\novertime pay beyond 40 hours\na week.\n1\ndeclared, \"The control of big\ncorporations through proxies so\nlicited by management and paid\nfor by the corporation, means\nthat control of the corporation\nand determination of executive\nsalaries rest in the Mme hand,\nthat of corporate management.\nThis is particularly true of Beth\nlehem Steel whose board of di\nrectors consists entirely of of\nficials of the company.\u201d The re\nport added that Bethlehem \u201cac\ncounted for 11 of the 18 highest\npaid executives in the United\nStates\nAnalyzing the method of re\nmuneration, the report found\nthat offering stock options to\nexecutives gives them a stake in\nthe market price of the securi\nties. Since the price of steel af\nfects the market price of the\nstocks, the subcommittee contin\nued, the system creates a \u201cbuilt\nin inflationary bias.\u201d\nSince 1951, U. S. Steel has of\nfered stock options to its top ex\necutive strata totaling a face\nvalue of $48,960,000. As of Aug\nust 8, 1957, the day U. S. Steel\u2019s\n'president, Roger Blough, began\ntestimony before the subcom\nmittee, the market value of these\nshares was $133,232,100.\nAFFECTIONATE TRIBUTE was paid former Sen. Herbert H. Lehman (D-N.Y.) at a luncheon in\nNew York given by groups within the Liberal Party in honor of his 80th birthday. Among the 1,500\npersons who joined in toasting Lehman (center) were (left to right) Pres. Alex Rose of the Hatters,\nAFL-CIO Pres. George Meany, Sen. James E. Murray (D-Mont.) and Sen. Paul Douglas (D-II).\nCommittee Clears\nWelfare Funds Bill\nProspects for passage of the AFL-CIO-endorsed bill to\nprotect employe welfare and pension plans got a major boost\nwhen the Senate Labor Committee voted overwhelming to\nsend the measure to the floor. The bill, sponsored by Sen.\nPaul H. Douglas (D-Ill.) and now co-sponsored with Admini\nstration backing by ben. Irv\ning M. Ives (R-N. Y.), would\nrequire reports to the federal\ngovernment on management of\nall money reserved for the bene\nfit of employes under welfare\nand pension programs.\nIn addition to requiring dis\nclosure of financial facts, wheth\ner the plans are administered by\nmanagement, unions or manage\nment and unions Jointly, the\nmeasure would make embezzle\nment of welfare money a federal\ncrime.\nThe bill has not yet been\nscheduled for Senate floor ac\ntion but committee sources point\nto the bipartisan majority favor\ning it in expressing a belief that\npassage is probable \u201csooner rath\ner than later\nGoldwater, Allott Opposed\n1\nAll committee Democrats ex\ncept Sen. Strom Thurmond (S.\nC.), who was absent, voted to re\nport the bill favorably. Three\nRepublicans voted for it and\none absentee. Sen. John Sher\nman Cooper (Ky.), also is on\nrecord as supporting the meas-i\nure. The only negative votes,\nwere cast by Senators Barry\nGoldwater (R-Ariz.) and Gor\nl\ndon Allott (R-Colo.).\nIn the House parallel welfare-1\nand-pension-plan measures are\nnow pending before the full La-;\nbor Committee headed by Rep.\nGraham Barden (D-N. C.). Lib\neral sources say they will move,\nto get committee action, based\non extensive hearings last year,\nno later than May 1.\nThe original Douglas bill re\nceived the strong support of the\nAFL-CIO last year when Pres.\nGeorge Meany testified in formal\nhearings in favor of strict dis\nI olnaiir* *eel======4$= 4. a..\nclosure requirements for the ad\nministrators of all welfare pro\ngrams.\nSuch action had been endorsed\nI\nby the 1955 merger convention\nof the AFL-CIO, and before\nmerger both the AFL and CIO\nindividually had requested that\nCongress act to protect workers\u2019\nbenefit funds from theft, mis\nmanagement or other abuses.\nLabor Sec. James P. Mitchell,\nwho originally proposed a more\nlimited disclosure bill for the\nAdministration, in effect swung\nhis support to the Douglas bill\nin 1957 testimony.\nInsurance Companies Fearful\nI\nI\nOpposition has come only\nfrom insurance companies, which\nhave quietly but insistently!\nclaimed that they feared an\nopening-wedge to federal \"reg\nulation,\u201d and from management:\ni\ntrade associations.\nThe U.S. Chamber of Com\nmerce, the National Association\nof Manufacturers, the American\nRetail Federation have argued in\nhearings that pension and wel-;\nfare programs administered sole\nly by management should be ex-i\nempt from disclosure require-1\nments. I\nNothing \"wrong\u201d in the han\ndling of such programs was ex-\nposed in hearings conducted in\n1954-56 by a subcommittee led\nby Senators Douglas and Ives,\nthe\nemployer spokesmen\nclaimed.\nDouglas Argues Need\nI\nDouglas hotly disputed this,\nand pointed out that the ex-i\nemption of employee-managed t\nplans would excuse from cov-i\nerage plans affecting the vast\nmajority of protected workers.\nIves, after sponsoring the more\nnarrow Adminstration program\noriginally, made it clear he sup\nported the broader approach. So\ndid Sec. Mitchell.\nAllott is expected to sponsor\nfloor amendments seeking to\nexempt employer administered I\nprograms. I\nI\nwe wringyou Shift Break\"\nI LISTEN to SHIFT BREAK\nwith GUY NUNN\nFeaturing MUSIC NEWS WEATHER SPORTS\nEvery Afternoon, Mon. thru Fri., 2:35 pm CKLW 800 kt on your diol\nl tes\npresented at a public service by the UAW\n[Labor Raps\nNeglect in\nSchool Crisis\nThe \u201cfrightening fact\" about\nour education problem is that\npoor schools and inadequate\nteaching will become \u201cworse, not\nbetter in the next few years\u201d un\nless present trends are reversed,;\nAFL-CIO Legislative Dir. An\ndrew J. Biemiller warned a\nHouse Education subcommittee.\nTestifying on the bill sponsored\nby Rep. Carl Elliott (D-Ala.) to\nestablish federal college scholar- j\nships for gifted students in the\nphysical sciences, Biemiller said:\n\u201cIt is a sound principle of\nlegislation that when we set\nout to meet a need, we plan to\nmeet the whole need, not only\nthat portion which has come\nmost lately to public atten\ntion.\u201d\nIt is \u201cshocking neglect\u201d by\nPres. Eisenhower to \u201cadvance no\nprogram to solve the general!\nclassroom shortage\u201d\u2014not even\nthe \u201cinadequate program of $1.3!\nbillion\" across four years that;\nthe Administration proposed last'\nyear but abandoned this year, he\nsaid.\nIke Suggests Deferment I\nThe President suggested that\nschool construction can be \u201cde\nferred,\" but U. S. Office of Edu\ncation reports showed a class\nroom shortage of 140,000 units\nlast September, an additional!\n44,000 needed by next Septem\nher and 220,000 needed in the\nj next\nfive\nyears\nfor\nhigher en\nrollment alone, Biemiller pointed\nlout.\nI\n\u201cProduction of babies con\ntinues to outstrip production\nof schools\" and federal aid for\nschool construction cannot be\n\u201cdeferred any longer,\u201d he said.\nThe problem of inadequate\nteachers\u2019 salaries also must be\nmet \u201chead on,\u201d he told the\nsubcommittee.\nThe average income of teach\ners last year was $4,330, he said,\nand only \u201ctwo states in the Un\nion\u201d had average salaries as high\nas $100 a week or $5,000 a year.\nYet the Heller Committee\u2019s Uni\nversity of California survey of\nfamily living standards set an\nannual income of $5,776 as need\ned for \u201cby no means luxurious\"\nstandards.\nTeachers Losing Out\nThe relative position of teach\ners in the salary scale is declin\ning, he continued, because their\nsalary increases are falling be\nhind rising living costs. \u201cIt is\nimpossible to attract and retain\nthe limited number of good\nteachers with such marginal and\nmeager compensation,\" he add\ned.\n\u201cA program of aid to uni\nversity graduate and under\ngraduate students,\u201d with em\nphasis on science, mathematics\nand foriegn languages, is not\nenough, Biemiller said.\n\u201cThe AFL-CIO believes we\nmust h a v e a program for all\nlevels of education,\u201d he testified.\nHe asked the committee to give\nspecific attention to bills for\nschool construction and federal\naid for teachers' salaries as well\nas for university science scholar\nships.\nEl\n0\nCOST OF LIVING Hits Alltime Peak: Workers\u2014espe\ncially factory workers\u2014are still getting the economic ax\nstuck in their necks, with little hope that it will be removed\nsoon. The Bureau of Labor Statistics reported that the cost\nof living zoomed o another alltime peak in February, the\nlatest date for which figures\nare available, while the aver\nage factory worker with\nthree dependents took home\n$1.28 less than he did in Feb\nruary 1957.\nLiving costs now have risen\nin 16 out of the last 18 months.\nThey stayed steady in the other\ntwo. A typical American fam\nily has seen its living expenses\nincrease some 61 percent dur\ning the past two years of \u201cEi\nsenhower-Nixon prosperity.\u201d\nThe profits-price spiral has\njacked up costs of ordinary\ngoods and services by 3.2 per\ncent since February of last year.\nAnd the housewife now has to\npay $12.25 for things that cost\nher only $10 in 1947-49.\nEven so, BLS Commissioner\nEwan Clague said \u201cI don\u2019t see\nmuch change on the downside\u201d\nfor the next few months. Of\ncourse, a drop in living costs\nmay not come even then\u2014de\nspite the recession.\nRising prices and fewer hours\nworked cut the purchasing pow\ner of the production worker\u2019s\ntake-home pay 5 per cent below\nwhat it was in February 1957.\ni\nROUGHLY HALF of Ameri\nca's major job markets are now\nsuffering from \u201csubstantial\u201d un\nemployment, according to the\nU.S. Labor Department. Twenty\nfive cities saw the number of\njobless workers rise above the\n6 per cent mark last month.\nThat brought the total number\nI of major job markets having at\nleast that much unemployment\nI to 70. In March 1957, only 19\nhad 6 percent or more of their\nworkers unemployed. There are\ni 149 such markets.\nI\nThe Department said that the\nnumber of persons without jobs\nhas increased in four fifths of\nthe large employment areas so\nfar this year.\nThe cities where especially\nlarge numbers of working men\nand women\u2014more than 12 per\ncent\u2014are looking for jobs are\ni Detroit, Altoona, Scranton and\nWilkes-Barre-Hazleton, Pa., and\nI\nProvidence, R. I.\nI\nPROSPERITY\u20141958 STYLE:\nBuilding contracts in February\nfell below levels of a year earl\nier for the third month in\na\nrow. They totaled $1.9 billion,\n10 per cent less than for Feb\nruary 1957 Steel operations\nare now running at the lower* c\nlevel, except during strike per\niods, since before World War II.\nThey are now at 50 per cent of\ncapacity. Steel manufacturers\nsay incoming business is not\nshowing the seasonal improve\nment that they had hoped for.\nTwo large manufacturers of\nhousehold appliances\u2014the Frigi\ndaire division of General Motors\nand Westinghouse E l e c t r i c\u2014\nhave announced production cut\nbacks and layoffs. Frigidaire is\nfurloughing 1,100 workers and\nsome salaried employees at its\nDayton, Ohio, plant; Westing\nhouse is closing its plant in\nColumbus, Ohio, for at least a\nweek.\nGeneral Motors, Ford and\nChrysler built 30 per cent fewer\nvehicles in the first three months\nof this year than they did dur\ning the same period of last yee\nFactory sales in February\"\nwere 12 per cent below what\nthey were in February 1957.\n\nNEW LOAN POLICY: \u201cThe re\ncent statements by Chairman\nDoerfer of the FCC and by\nWhite House spokesman James\nHagerty that they saw nothing\nwrong with the loan of color\ntelevision sets to themselves\u2014\nsince this enabled them to keep\ntrack of what was happening in\nthe i n d u s t r y\u2014are of course\nsound statements of \u2018wisdom and\ndedication.\u2019 The thing to do now\nis to extend this noble doctrine\nthroughout the Government.\n\u201cI suggest therefore that we\nsee that private railraod cars\nare \u2018loaned\u2019 to the members of\nthe Interstate Commerce Com\nmission\nand\nof\ncourse\nto M\nHagerty, so that they may know?\nwhat is going on with the rail\nMr.\n0%\nroads; that private airplanes be\n\u2018loaned\u2019 to the members of the\nCAA and the CAB and of course\nMr. Hagerty, so that they may\nkeep a more watchful eye on\nairplane operations; and per\nhaps we might go so far as to\n\u2018loan\u2019 stock of various corpora\ntions to members of the Secur\nities and Exchange Commission\nand of course to Mr. Hagerty,\njso that they might have that\npeculiar sensation of knowing\nwhat it is like to have your\nI stock go up or down as the case\nmay be.\u201d\u2014Marshall MacDuffie\nin letter to Washington Post\nand Times Herald, March 29,\n1958.\nI CROSSWORD\nPUZZLE\nLAST WEK\u2019s\nANSWER\nCo\ntR(E] -1A\"s\nACROSS\n1. Princess\n(Moham.)\n6 Singing\ngroup\n11. Ascended\n123. Door joint\n18. Fathers\n14. Boxing area\n15. Diocesan\ncenter\n16. Single\n18. Fish\n19. Esker\n2. American\nIndians\n3. Pierce\n4. Employ\n5. Com\nmuns\ncation\n\u2022.Soft\nlimestone\nEmploy\n8. Undivided\n9. Lit\n10. Primera\n22. Re\nmitted\n23. Slope\n34. Kind\nof\nsand*\nwich\n35. Crosby\nis one\n26. Par.\nJEI .'Barasp\nGHME USCIIB\n\"smin OTEO\nOOJRI Odd\nUNEEH]id (OJ\nEINE\nII\u2019\nIB\nnm slHVGlis]\nJnitV ebe an\nHhiH MOL\"\nGI\u2019E [39/H3\nOCU]id\n(30 EEH3\n30. Bird of prey 20 Firm\n31. Elder\nIT. Be in debt 30. Fat\nST* r-m _\n38. Red dictator 34. Burden\nI\n31. Devoured\n32. Knight\u2019s\nattendant\n28. A row\n34. Frighten\n38. Obeys\n37. Hot and dry\n28. Measure\nof length\n29. Pole\n80. Malt Min\n81. Gallium\n(sym.)\n83. Perform\n34. Hautboy\n35. Land\nmeasures\n38. Silly\n38. Half\ndiameters\n40. Title of\nruler (Eth.)\n41. Beast of\nburden\n(8. A.)\n43. Rub out\n43. Mandarin\u2019s\nresidence\nDOWN\n1. Baas singer\n31. Dirt\n32. Of a\ncontinent\n35. First man\n37. Moslem\ntitle\n39. Wing\n(Fr.)\nVIKUIL\nSoMLBo0V DIDN\u2019T\nWIPE THEIR FEET\nWHALN THE4\nCAME IN!\nSOMSteoy DIDN\u2019T\n77.\nWANG OP HIS\n_ COAT?\nA\n\nTS\u201d\nWELL-AT\nLEAST THEY\nTHNK T\u2019M\nsose0py.\n1\nC\nMOTT AND JEFF\n1 WANNA\nCHARGE IT.\nMR. BRIGLEY!\nO.K,\ngI\nara\nCo\nCseed,\ng)\nI KNEW IT\nWOULD\nHAPPEN\n8%\nBY AL SMITH\n05\nbo\n\nAL\nSut\u2014%\nGRANDMA\nI\nette\nJ**.\n*74*6\nEs\n*Tt\n1\nss\nl!\nr\n\n.\"m\n\u201cf\n\n1\n\n\n9\nS\nBy Charles Kuhn\nTHERE,THAT'LL KEEP TH COLD FROM\nGETTIN\u2019 TH\u2019 PURTY LITTLE THINGS\nFOR AWHILE LONGER. ANYWAY- J\ni**\nS\n6\nJITTER\nwa\u2019ve GOT TO DEVELOP A\nSTRONSER GW&O IF WE WAAT\nt wr TAT TANKMOUSE TEAM\n\nV.\ne t\n1.\nFG5\n\nX\n.4\nBy ARTHUR POITER\ni.\n9u\n\nCc\naanom\"\nild","height":"26840","width":"19464"}}
